JavaScript errors occur when the code contains mistakes that prevent execution. Errors can be syntax errors, runtime errors, or logical errors.

1.Types of Errors in JavaScript
  1ï¸âƒ£Syntax Errors (Parsing Errors)
    ğŸ’ What? Mistakes in the code structure that prevent execution.
    ğŸ’ Example:
 _______________________________________________________________
|  console.log("Hello World"  // Missing closing parenthesis    |
|_______________________________________________________________|
ğŸ”´ Error Message: Uncaught SyntaxError: Unexpected end of input


2ï¸âƒ£ Reference Errors
  ğŸ’ What? Occur when trying to use an undefined variable.
  ğŸ’ Example:
 _______________________________________________________________
|  console.log(name); // 'name' is not defined                  |
|_______________________________________________________________|
ğŸ”´ Error Message: Uncaught ReferenceError: name is not defined


3ï¸âƒ£ Type Errors
  ğŸ’ What? Occur when trying to use a value in an invalid way.
  ğŸ’ Example:

 _______________________________________________________________
|  let num = 10;                                                |
|  num();  // num is not a function                             | 
|_______________________________________________________________|
ğŸ”´ Error Message: Uncaught TypeError: num is not a function


4ï¸âƒ£ Range Errors
  ğŸ’ What? Occur when a number is outside the allowed range.
  ğŸ’ Example:

 _______________________________________________________________
|  let arr = new Array(-5); // Negative array size              |
|_______________________________________________________________|
ğŸ”´ Error Message: Uncaught RangeError: Invalid array length

5ï¸âƒ£ Logical Errors (Bugs)
  ğŸ’ What? Code runs but produces the wrong output due to incorrect logic.
  ğŸ’ Example:
  
 ____________________________________________________________________________________
|  let total = 10 + "5";  // Expected 15, but result is "105" (string concatenation) |
|  console.log(total);                                                               | 
|____________________________________________________________________________________|
ğŸŸ¡ No error message, but incorrect behavior!


2. Handling Errors in JavaScript
Using try...catch
ğŸ‘‰ Prevents crashes by catching errors.

 ___________________________________________________________
|  try {                                                    |
|      let x = undefinedVar; // Undefined variable          |    
|  } catch (error) {                                        |
|      console.log("An error occurred: " + error.message);  |
|  }                                                        |          
|___________________________________________________________|
âœ… Output: An error occurred: undefinedVar is not defined

